'The sea is ours': Bolivia, landlocked country, hopes the court will reopen a road to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rope-covered naval base in La Paz.
Public buildings fly a navy blue flag.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon carry the slogan: "The sea is ours by right.
To recover it is a duty".
Throughout Bolivia, a landlocked country, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still alive, as is the longing to once again sail the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps at their highest point in decades as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, the spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, a positive outlook on the outcome", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ICTY ruling on giant screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of their country's claim, so that after decades of uncertain negotiations, Chile will be forced to negotiate, granting Bolivia a sovereign outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic Bolivian indigenous president who faces a controversial re-election battle next year, also has a lot at stake in Monday's ruling.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean", were the president's vows last August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Bolivia, and that little would change even if it did.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, has no powers to assign Chilean territory to another country and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the judgment of the ICTY is handed down only six months after the final arguments were heard indicates that the case "was not complicated", said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from advancing the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have hurt it.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration", Zárate said.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric has undermined some residual Chilean goodwill, he suggested.
At some point in the future, Bolivia and Chile will continue the talks, but it will be extremely difficult to maintain dialogue after this.
The two countries haven't exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making process was unusually swift.
Next Monday will give Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a possibility to "put an end to 139 years of disagreements for mutual benefit", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean", he added.
"The sentence is an opportunity to understand that we must move beyond the past".
