John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, and this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional test scores, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With over 30 000 pupils spread across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the highest level of service for both pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further study and university entry, as well as for their chosen careers and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought-after subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you can get into his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can reach his heart".
This quote is a good reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people in other countries.
Based on the results of the recent exams this year, we find that languages are at the top of the table, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the maximum grade of A.
These data, collected from the 74 schools under the SCIS, show that 72% of pupils obtained the maximum A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are promoting foreign languages as vital skills which will undoubtedly serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now looked at in the same way as STEM subjects in the curricula of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that among the reasons for employers' difficulty filling vacancies, 17% related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowing other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the younger generation for their future careers.
With more potential job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with a life skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a double-digit proportion, 15%.
So investing now in language education is important for today's children.
The knowledge of several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding relevant employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages they teach.
Some will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be a language choice in independent schools, supported by specialist teaching staff.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing an educational environment that prepares children and gives them the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance for the future of the country.
In fact, modern languages should be considered 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to provide this option with diversity and excellence for young Scots.
It must be done.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
