North Korea says "not even thinking" about unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were worsening mistrust of the United States and that there was no way the country could unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" in the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the US", he said.
"Without trust in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances there is no way we can proceed to our disarmament first".
While Ri recycled well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statements appear significant in that they do not reject unilateral denuclearization outright, in contrast to Pyongyang's previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit held between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, opposing it until the 'declaration of the end of the war'", Ri said.
"The realization that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream for people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the prolongation of sanctions is exacerbating our distrust".
Ri No mentioned plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been mentioned by the US leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: "If the interested party in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have reached this impasse".
Still, Ri's tone of speech was drastically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea's rockets toward US soil was inevitable after "Mr. President Mau" Trump called Kim the "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year had threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but said much more had to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea's denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for such a move, saying that "whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until denuclearisation is complete, final and verifiable".
The Security Council unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea imposed since 2006 in an attempt to strangle funding for North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later stated that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit didn't go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, though North Korea later denounced him for "making gangster demands.
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States "takes appropriate measures".
Pompeo said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" they were seeking were the security guarantees taken by Trump in Singapore, as well as initiatives toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course that teaches them to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has put all of its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the sexist culture of studying in caffeinated "direct courses".
One professor concluded that the students of this world-class university often had no idea about the most basic concepts about self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, authored the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for this course came after I gave a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
And at the end, a girl came up to me and said, "Why are you only telling me this in senior year?"
The young woman said that no one had ever mentioned to her the importance of sleep, which surprised me", she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance as well as to improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the institution decided to introduce the course after finding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section is a picture of a dorm where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how poor sleep affects athletic performance, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it's not going to change students' behavior instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as we all have a right to know about the health effects of the choice to smoke", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "making direct" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we get enough quality sleep should be a "secret weapon" for students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to prevent them from getting fat, since sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of physical biology and chemistry, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year as a freshman at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a campus-wide course, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all postgraduate students to attend a similar study programme before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider using an alarm for bedtime, as well as for waking up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" from electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
