Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our Sunday Morning Almanac: on September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today and counting, the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A staple of science ever since, the Geiger counter has also become a staple of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" starring the unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms released by radioactivity in the minerals".
Evans: "Look, now it's really cracking!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that gave it its name still lives on.
New cancer vaccine teaches immune system to "see" harmful cells
A new cancer vaccine trains the immune system to "see" harmful cells and kill them
