The method involves removing immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine".
HER2 "controls the growth of several cancers", including breast, ovarian, lung, and colorectal cancers, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach involving removing immune cells from patients and "teaching" them to attack cancer cells has worked in treating one type of leukemia.
