HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% jump in the number of its citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected in the country, health authorities said.
Around 40 000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The vast majority of new cases result from transmission through sexual relations, which marks a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, in terms of annual variation, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
HIV transmission through sexual intercourse is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community is said to be widespread.
Studies have estimated that because of the country's conservative values, 70 to 90 percent of men who have had sex with other men end up marrying women.
Many of the transmission of disease results from inadequate sexual protection in these relationships.
The Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication since 2003 as part of an effort to address the problem.
